column6: My guess is that Facebook is going to become a regulated utility within the next 3 or 4 years. Everything it does is going to be closely regulated, if not in the US then in other territories (e.g. the EU). What data Facebook collects on users will be regulated. Who Facebook makes user data available to will be regulated. The veracity of posts by users will be regulated. The removal of illegal posts will be regulated. Facebook will be responsible for illegal acts carried out via its platforms. In short Facebook and other social media sites will be treated other forms of media. This will affect its costs and probably reduce its share price.

Facebook's market capitalization has decreased nearly $200B since July 2018. Still, historical trends indicate a rebound is foreseeable. The company has worked to extensively address the challenges it faced from states utilizing the platform as a vector for disinformation and political warfare. The number of worldwide monthly users of Facebook continues to trend upward with the upcoming U.S. midterm elections helping to bolster usage. The platform will continue to regain value as it remains the most popular social media platform in the world.

Facebook is likely to further see a decrease in its market capitalization due in large part to the negative perception of the company's track record in safeguarding customers' sensitive data. Despite achieving and operating in an almost-monopolistic environment in the field of online social media and social networking services, a positive capitalization growth trend beginning in 2014, and an all-time peak market capitalization of 602 billion dollars in July 2018, the company lost about 180 billion dollars in the last three months. (source is Ycharts, https://ycharts.com/companies/FB/market_cap). Furthermore, the company has been recently fined by a UK watchdog $644,000 over users’ data breach in Cambridge Analytica scandal (https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2018/10/25/uk-watchdog-fines-facebook-data-breach-cambridge-analytica/1759632002/).

Facebook has also been plagued by a few scandals, such as the Cambridge Analytica scandal in March 2018, leading to some of its biggest drops until now (http://fortune.com/2018/03/19/facebook-stock-share-price-cambridge-analytica-donald-trump/). Facebook is also having an issue with slowing growth in numbers of daily active users, a huge factor in ad spending. (https://www.recode.net/2018/7/25/17614426/facebook-fb-earnings-q2-2018-user-growth-troubles). Still, overall Facebook’s growth has been quite impressive. While FB has faced recent challenges that impact their market cap dramatically, I believe by Dec 28 this company will adapt to the changing circumstances in a manner that assures investors (and confronts shorts) on their continued value growth opportunities over the long run. Though they have made missteps, they still have many resources and have overcome challenges in the past. The platform is simply too widespread to permanently impair global promise of future returns. Also, many of the challenges are in the US & EU, yet FB's worldwide opportunities continue to grow and mature in many other regional markets - and situation that, taken as a whole, offset some of the offsets in US/EU business operations. Consider that FB's customer & consumer base outside of US/EU is larger & that this portion economically is growing on a per capita basis.

Its on a P/E of over 26 which would suggest that investors expect it to continue growing strongly. I see two reasons to think that is too high. First the P/E of most US stocks is higher than the historic norms, which suggests at some point US stocks can be expected to fall back to historic norms (they always say "its different this time, they will not fall", but they always do). The second reason is that Facebook's business model is having to change. The fact that the US politicians seems to have no idea what that business model was possibly indicates that some investors are equally ignorant, but it is clear that the world is changing. Users and regulators are taking a lot of interest in social media, "free" services, ownership of personal data, and who can do what with it, fake news, racist, sexist and illegal comments, interference in democracy, the high profits and low taxes paid by the companies. Facebook has so many users who spend so much time using it that the likelihood of more usage does not seem very likely, but even before the CA issue the hours of usage in the US was already dropping. And had dropped a lot among the younger age groups. There are reports that 10% of US user have left in the last few weeks (some may come back, other may leave). The average hours of use will probably continue to fall in the US and within the next year or two will probably start dropping worldwide. All social media companies will need to employ a lot more people policing their sites as they will increasing be required to clean up their act. If the US is slow to act the EU shows signs of forcing the pace (why not? Facebook takes business from European firms, but does not employ many Europeans or pay much European tax, making life uncomfortable for Facebook is a win/win for every European politician, believer in driving out fake news, and raising tax (or fines)). Other countries around the world will take note of the control that China has over social media, and wondering why they don't follow suit. So bashing Facebook is something that liberals and conservatives can agree on. I don't think the Facebook investors have seen the train coming, they are standing on the tracks thinking nothing happened.
Collective amnesia. The 24 hour news cycle will move on to the next scandal. Stock barely dipped and Wall Street piled back in after seeing how incompetent the politicians were.
FB will go the way of MySpace and the NFL, picked on the wrong people and lied about it.
